Topic: Population and Samples#

Definitions:#

  • Population: The entire set of possible data points.

  • Sample: A subset taken from the population for analysis.

\[ \text{Population size} = N, \quad \text{Sample size} = n \]

Use in Financial Forecasting:#

  • Population: All trades in the stock market over 10 years.

  • Sample: Trades from the last 1 year for a specific analysis.

Importance of Sampling#

  • Cost-effective

  • Time-saving

  • Enables inference and forecasting

Types of Sampling in Finance#

  • Random Sampling: Each item has an equal chance of being selected.

  • Stratified Sampling: The population is divided into strata, and a random sample is taken from each.

  • Systematic Sampling: Selecting items at a regular interval.

  • Cluster Sampling: Sampling entire groups or clusters within the population.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# 1. Simulate a population of 10,000 daily stock returns
np.random.seed(42)
population_size = 10000
population_returns = np.random.normal(loc=0.0001, scale=0.01, size=population_size)
population_df = pd.DataFrame({'Daily Return': population_returns})

# Add a 'Sector' column for stratified and cluster sampling examples
sectors = np.random.choice(['Tech', 'Finance', 'Consumer', 'Healthcare'], size=population_size)
population_df['Sector'] = sectors

print("Population of Stock Returns with Sector (first 5 rows):")
print(population_df.head())
print(f"\nPopulation Size: {len(population_df)}")

# --- 2. Random Sampling ---
sample_random = population_df.sample(n=500, random_state=42)
print("\n--- Random Sampling ---")
print("Random Sample (first 5 rows):\n", sample_random.head())
print(f"Random Sample Size: {len(sample_random)}")

# --- 3. Stratified Sampling ---
# Sample 100 returns from each sector and keep the 'Sector' column
sampled_list = []
grouped = population_df.groupby('Sector', group_keys=False)
for name, group in grouped:
    sampled = group.sample(n=100, random_state=42)
    sampled_list.append(sampled)

sample_stratified = pd.concat(sampled_list)
print("\n--- Stratified Sampling ---")
print("Stratified Sample (first few rows):\n", sample_stratified.head())
print(f"Stratified Sample Size: {len(sample_stratified)}")
print("Value counts per sector in stratified sample:\n", sample_stratified['Sector'].value_counts())

# --- 4. Systematic Sampling ---
# Select every 20th return
sampling_interval = 20
indices = np.arange(0, len(population_df), sampling_interval)
sample_systematic = population_df.iloc[indices]
print("\n--- Systematic Sampling ---")
print("Systematic Sample (first 5 rows):\n", sample_systematic.head())
print(f"Systematic Sample Size: {len(sample_systematic)}")

# --- 5. Cluster Sampling ---
# Sample 2 random sectors and take all returns from those sectors
rng = np.random.default_rng(seed=42) # Create a random number generator
unique_sectors = population_df['Sector'].unique()
sampled_sectors = rng.choice(unique_sectors, size=2, replace=False) # Use the rng object
sample_cluster = population_df[population_df['Sector'].isin(sampled_sectors)]
print("\n--- Cluster Sampling ---")
print("Sampled Sectors:", sampled_sectors)
print("Cluster Sample (first few rows):\n", sample_cluster.head())
print(f"Cluster Sample Size: {len(sample_cluster)}")
print("Value counts per sector in cluster sample:\n", sample_cluster['Sector'].value_counts())
# --- Visualization (Optional) ---
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 10))

plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
sns.histplot(population_df['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='skyblue', label='Population')
sns.histplot(sample_random['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='salmon', alpha=0.6, label='Random Sample')
plt.title('Random Sampling')
plt.xlabel('Daily Return')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.legend()

plt.subplot(2, 2, 2)
sns.histplot(population_df['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='skyblue', label='Population')
sns.histplot(sample_stratified['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='lightgreen', alpha=0.6, label='Stratified Sample')
plt.title('Stratified Sampling')
plt.xlabel('Daily Return')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.legend()

plt.subplot(2, 2, 3)
sns.histplot(population_df['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='skyblue', label='Population')
sns.histplot(sample_systematic['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='orange', alpha=0.6, label='Systematic Sample')
plt.title('Systematic Sampling')
plt.xlabel('Daily Return')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.legend()

plt.subplot(2, 2, 4)
sns.histplot(population_df['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='skyblue', label='Population')
sns.histplot(sample_cluster['Daily Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='purple', alpha=0.6, label='Cluster Sample')
plt.title('Cluster Sampling')
plt.xlabel('Daily Return')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Simulate population: returns of a stock over 10,000 days
np.random.seed(0)
population_returns = np.random.normal(loc=0.01, scale=0.03, size=10000)

# Take a random sample of 500 returns
sample_returns = np.random.choice(population_returns, size=500, replace=False)

# Convert to DataFrames
df_pop = pd.DataFrame({'Return': population_returns})
df_sample = pd.DataFrame({'Return': sample_returns})

# Mean comparison
pop_mean = df_pop['Return'].mean()
sample_mean = df_sample['Return'].mean()

# Visual comparison of population and sample
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
sns.kdeplot(df_pop['Return'], label='Population', linewidth=2)
sns.kdeplot(df_sample['Return'], label='Sample', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
plt.title("Population vs Sample Return Distribution")
plt.xlabel("Return")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Topic: Frequency Distribution and Histogram#

Frequency Distribution#

A frequency distribution shows how often values occur in different intervals (called bins). It helps summarize large data sets in a visual format.

Use in Finance:#

  • Grouping daily returns into ranges to assess volatility

  • Analyzing how often a stock achieves specific return bands

Example:#

If we categorize returns into bins of 0.01 width, we can count:

  • How many days returns were between -0.01 and 0.00?

  • How many days returns were between 0.01 and 0.02?

Histogram#

A histogram is a bar chart representing a frequency distribution.

  • x-axis = value intervals (bins)

  • y-axis = frequency count

Histograms are helpful in:

  • Understanding distribution shape (normal, skewed, etc.)

  • Detecting outliers

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Simulate daily returns for 500 days
np.random.seed(42)
returns = np.random.normal(loc=0.001, scale=0.02, size=500)

# Convert to DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame({'Return': returns})

# Create frequency bins
bins = np.arange(-0.1, 0.1, 0.01)
df['Bin'] = pd.cut(df['Return'], bins)

# Frequency distribution table
freq_table = df['Bin'].value_counts().sort_index()
freq_table = freq_table.reset_index()
freq_table.columns = ['Return Interval', 'Frequency']

Topic: Percentiles and Quartiles#

A percentile is a measure that indicates the value below which a given percentage of observations in a group falls.

  • The $p^{\text{th}}$ percentile ($0 < p < 100$) is the value below which $p%$ of the data falls.

Quartiles are specific percentiles that divide the data into four equal parts:

  • Q1 (1st quartile) = $25^{\text{th}}$ percentile

  • Q2 (2nd quartile or median) = $50^{\text{th}}$ percentile

  • Q3 (3rd quartile) = $75^{\text{th}}$ percentile

These help summarize the distribution of the data and are used in box plots and descriptive statistics.

Mathematical Formulation#

Given a sorted dataset $X = {x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n}$:

The $p^{\text{th}}$ percentile is computed by finding the value at the rank:

\[ r = \frac{p}{100} \cdot (n + 1) \]

If $r$ is not an integer, we interpolate between the values at the positions $\lfloor r \rfloor$ and $\lceil r \rceil$.

Interpretation#

  • Q1: 25% of the data lies below this value.

  • Q2 (Median): Half of the data lies below this value.

  • Q3: 75% of the data lies below this value.

These values can be used to measure spread, skewness, and detect outliers when used with the interquartile range (IQR).

Bonus: Interquartile Range (IQR)#

The IQR is the range between Q3 and Q1:

\[ \text{IQR} = Q3 - Q1 \]

This helps in identifying the middle 50% of the data and is used in outlier detection.

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import scipy.stats as stats

# Sample normally distributed data
np.random.seed(42)
data = np.random.normal(loc=50, scale=10, size=1000)

# Compute desired percentiles
q15, q1, q2, q3 = np.percentile(data, [15, 25, 50, 75])

# Create histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
count, bins, ignored = plt.hist(data, bins=30, density=True, alpha=0.6, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black', label='Histogram')

# Fit a normal distribution and plot it
mu, std = np.mean(data), np.std(data)
xmin, xmax = plt.xlim()
x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
p = stats.norm.pdf(x, mu, std)
plt.plot(x, p, 'k', linewidth=2, label=rf'Normal Fit\n$\mu={mu:.2f}$, $\sigma={std:.2f}$')

# Add vertical lines for percentiles
plt.axvline(q15, color='purple', linestyle='--', label='15th Percentile')
plt.axvline(q1, color='green', linestyle='--', label='Q1 (25%)')
plt.axvline(q2, color='blue', linestyle='--', label='Q2 / Median (50%)')
plt.axvline(q3, color='red', linestyle='--', label='Q3 (75%)')

# Annotate values
for q, label in zip([q15, q1, q2, q3], ['15th', 'Q1', 'Q2', 'Q3']):
    plt.text(q, plt.ylim()[1]*0.9, f'{label} = {q:.2f}', rotation=90, verticalalignment='center')

# Plot aesthetics
plt.title('Histogram with Normal Distribution, Quartiles, and 15th Percentile')
plt.xlabel('Value')
plt.ylabel('Density')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

3. Visualization: Box Plot#

Box plots (or box-and-whisker plots) are a great way to visualize the distribution of numerical data using five-number summary statistics:

  • 📦 Box: Spans from Q1 to Q3 (interquartile range, IQR)

  • 📍 Line inside box: Represents the median (Q2)

  • 📏 Whiskers: Extend to the last data points within $1.5 \times \text{IQR}$ from Q1 and Q3

  • ❗ Outliers: Data points beyond $Q1 - 1.5 \times \text{IQR}$ or $Q3 + 1.5 \times \text{IQR}$

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Generate sample data
np.random.seed(42)
data = np.random.normal(loc=50, scale=10, size=100)

# Compute statistics
q1 = np.percentile(data, 25)
q2 = np.percentile(data, 50)  # Median
q3 = np.percentile(data, 75)
iqr = q3 - q1

# Whisker bounds
lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr

# Identify outliers
outliers = data[(data < lower_bound) | (data > upper_bound)]

# Create box plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
box = plt.boxplot(data, vert=False, patch_artist=True, showfliers=True,
                  boxprops=dict(facecolor='lightblue'),
                  flierprops=dict(marker='o', markerfacecolor='red', markersize=8, linestyle='none'),
                  medianprops=dict(color='blue', linewidth=2),
                  whiskerprops=dict(color='black'),
                  capprops=dict(color='black'))

# Annotations
plt.axvline(q1, color='green', linestyle='--', label=f'Q1 = {q1:.2f}')
plt.axvline(q2, color='blue', linestyle='--', label=f'Median = {q2:.2f}')
plt.axvline(q3, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Q3 = {q3:.2f}')
plt.axvline(lower_bound, color='gray', linestyle=':', label=f'Lower whisker = {lower_bound:.2f}')
plt.axvline(upper_bound, color='gray', linestyle=':', label=f'Upper whisker = {upper_bound:.2f}')

# Add title and legend
plt.title('Box Plot: Visualization of Quartiles and Outliers')
plt.xlabel('Value')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Topic: Cross Tabulation#

Cross tabulation, also known as a contingency table, is a statistical tool used to analyze the relationship between two or more categorical variables. It presents the joint frequency distribution of the variables in a matrix format.

If we have two categorical variables:

  • Variable $A$ with $m$ categories: $A_1, A_2, \dots, A_m$

  • Variable $B$ with $n$ categories: $B_1, B_2, \dots, B_n$

Then the contingency table $T$ is an $m \times n$ matrix where each entry $T_{ij}$ represents the frequency count for the combination $(A_i, B_j)$:

\[\begin{split} T = \begin{bmatrix} T_{11} & T_{12} & \cdots & T_{1n} \\ T_{21} & T_{22} & \cdots & T_{2n} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ T_{m1} & T_{m2} & \cdots & T_{mn} \end{bmatrix} \end{split}\]

Each row corresponds to a category of variable $A$, and each column to a category of variable $B$.

💼 Use in Finance#

Cross tabulation is useful in many financial applications, such as:

  • ✅ Customer Segmentation vs. Investment Type:

    • Understand if customers with different profiles prefer equity, debt, or gold.

  • ✅ Credit Rating vs. Loan Defaults:

    • Check how default rates vary across credit ratings.

  • ✅ Trading Volume vs. Sector:

    • Analyze whether trading volume concentration is sector-dependent.

🧪 Example Setup#

Suppose we analyze how different risk preferences affect investment types.

  • Risk Preference (Rows): ['High', 'Medium', 'Low']

  • Investment Type (Columns): ['Equity', 'Debt', 'Gold']

This would give us a $3 \times 3$ cross-tabulation table:

3. Normalize Cross Tab (Percentage)#

Use normalize='index' to get proportions (row-wise).

# Normalized cross-tab (row-wise percentages)
cross_tab_percent = pd.crosstab(data['Investment Type'], data['Risk Preference'], normalize='index')
cross_tab_percent.round(2)
Risk Preference High Low Medium
Investment Type
Debt 0.23 0.41 0.36
Equity 0.33 0.27 0.39
Gold 0.45 0.32 0.23

  • $T_{ij}$ = raw frequency count for row category $i$ and column category $j$

  • $R_i = \sum_{j=1}^{n} T_{ij}$ = row total for row $i$

Then, the row-wise normalized value for cell $(i, j)$ is:

\[ P_{ij} = \frac{T_{ij}}{R_i} \]

This represents the percentage of row $i$ that falls into column category $j$.

So the normalized cross-tab matrix becomes:

\[\begin{split} P = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{T_{11}}{R_1} & \frac{T_{12}}{R_1} & \cdots & \frac{T_{1n}}{R_1} \\ \frac{T_{21}}{R_2} & \frac{T_{22}}{R_2} & \cdots & \frac{T_{2n}}{R_2} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ \frac{T_{m1}}{R_m} & \frac{T_{m2}}{R_m} & \cdots & \frac{T_{mn}}{R_m} \end{bmatrix} \end{split}\]

Each row now sums to 1 (or 100% if multiplied by 100).

\[ P_{\text{Equity, High}} = \frac{T_{\text{Equity, High}}}{T_{\text{Equity, High}} + T_{\text{Equity, Medium}} + T_{\text{Equity, Low}}} \]

0.4520547945205479

Topic: Descriptive Statistical Measures#

1. What Are Descriptive Statistics?#

Descriptive statistics provide quantitative summaries of data, helping analysts understand:

  • Central values

  • Variation and risk

  • Distribution characteristics

  • Daily Returns: Summarize typical gain/loss behavior

  • Volatility Analysis: Quantify risk and fluctuation

  • Distributional Insights: Identify fat tails, skewness for option pricing or VaR

Central Tendency#

Mean:#

Average return over a period.

\[ \bar{x} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i \]

Used to estimate expected returns.

Median:#

Middle value when sorted. Resistant to outliers.

Mode:#

Most frequent value (rarely used for financial returns).

Dispersion Measures#

Range:#

\[ \text{Range} = \max(x) - \min(x) \]

Variance:#

\[ \sigma^2 = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i - \bar{x})^2 \]

Standard Deviation:#

\[ \sigma = \sqrt{\sigma^2} \]

Used as a proxy for volatility in finance.

Shape of Distribution#

Skewness:#

Indicates asymmetry of returns.

\[ \text{Skewness} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( \frac{x_i - \bar{x}}{\sigma} \right)^3 \]

  • $\text{Skewness} > 0$: Long right tail (lottery-type returns)

  • $\text{Skewness} < 0$: Long left tail (crash risk)

Kurtosis:#

Measures tailedness (peakedness) of the distribution.

\[ \text{Kurtosis} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( \frac{x_i - \bar{x}}{\sigma} \right)^4 \]

  • $\text{Kurtosis} > 3$: Heavy tails (risk of outliers)

  • $\text{Kurtosis} < 3$: Light tails (more stable)

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Simulate 100 daily returns from a normal distribution (mean=0.001, std=0.02)
np.random.seed(42)
returns = np.random.normal(loc=0.001, scale=0.02, size=100)

# Convert to DataFrame
data = pd.DataFrame({'Return': returns})

# Summary statistics
summary = {
    'Mean': data['Return'].mean(),
    'Median': data['Return'].median(),
    'Std Dev': data['Return'].std(),
    'Variance': data['Return'].var(),
    'Skewness': data['Return'].skew(),
    'Kurtosis': data['Return'].kurt()
}
print(pd.Series(summary).round(4))

# Plot histogram with KDE
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.histplot(data['Return'], bins=30, kde=True, color='skyblue')
plt.title('Simulated Daily Returns Distribution')
plt.xlabel('Daily Return')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Topic: Cluster Analysis#

Cluster analysis is an unsupervised machine learning technique used to group similar data points together. It identifies patterns in data without prior knowledge of the group labels.

Use in Finance:#

  • Segmenting customers based on spending behavior

  • Grouping stocks with similar price movements

  • Identifying risk groups in portfolios

K-Means Clustering#

  • Partitions data into K clusters.

  • Each data point is assigned to the cluster with the nearest centroid.

Hierarchical Clustering#

  • Builds a tree-like structure (dendrogram) to group data.

DBSCAN (Density-Based Spatial Clustering)#

  • Groups points that are closely packed together.

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.animation import FuncAnimation
from IPython.display import HTML, display
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, DBSCAN
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage, dendrogram, fcluster
import matplotlib.cm as cm

# Set random seed for reproducibility
np.random.seed(42)

# Generate synthetic stock data with more distinct clusters
n_samples = 100
cluster_means = [(-1, -1), (1, 1), (1, -1), (-1, 1)]  # More distinct clusters
X = np.vstack([
    np.random.normal(mean, 0.3, (n_samples//4, 2)) for mean in cluster_means
])
X = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)  # Standardize features

# --- K-Means Clustering Animation ---
def animate_kmeans():
    k = 4  # Number of clusters (matches our generated data)
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init='random', n_init=1, max_iter=1)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    scatter = ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c='gray', alpha=0.6)
    ax.set_xlabel('Mean Daily Return (Standardized)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Volatility (Standardized)')
    ax.set_title('K-Means Clustering Animation')
    centroids = np.random.randn(k, 2)  # Random initial centroids
    centroid_scatter = ax.scatter(centroids[:, 0], centroids[:, 1], c='red', marker='x', s=200, linewidths=3)

    def update(frame):
        ax.clear()
        if frame == 0:
            scatter = ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c='gray', alpha=0.6)
            centroids = np.random.randn(k, 2)
            centroid_scatter = ax.scatter(centroids[:, 0], centroids[:, 1], c='red', marker='x', s=200, linewidths=3)
        else:
            kmeans.max_iter = frame
            kmeans.fit(X)
            labels = kmeans.labels_
            centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_
            scatter = ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=labels, cmap='rainbow', alpha=0.6)
            centroid_scatter = ax.scatter(centroids[:, 0], centroids[:, 1], c='red', marker='x', s=200, linewidths=3)
        
        ax.set_xlabel('Mean Daily Return (Standardized)')
        ax.set_ylabel('Volatility (Standardized)')
        ax.set_title(f'K-Means Clustering (Iteration {frame})')
        return scatter, centroid_scatter

    ani = FuncAnimation(fig, update, frames=range(8), interval=800, blit=False)
    plt.close(fig)
    return HTML(ani.to_jshtml())

# --- Hierarchical Clustering Animation (Enhanced) ---
def animate_hierarchical():
    Z = linkage(X, method='ward')
    n_merges = len(Z)
    n_frames = min(15, n_merges + 1)  # Show more merge steps
    
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 6))
    scatter = ax1.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c='gray', alpha=0.6)
    ax1.set_xlabel('Mean Daily Return (Standardized)')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Volatility (Standardized)')
    ax1.set_title('Hierarchical Clustering Animation')
    ax2.set_title('Dendrogram')
    
    # Initial clusters: each point is its own cluster
    labels = np.arange(len(X))
    clusters = {i: [i] for i in range(len(X))}

    def update(frame):
        ax1.clear()
        ax2.clear()
        
        if frame > 0:
            # Process the merge for this frame
            cluster1, cluster2 = int(Z[frame-1, 0]), int(Z[frame-1, 1])
            new_cluster = len(X) + frame - 1
            
            # Update labels for points in these clusters
            for j in range(len(X)):
                if labels[j] in [cluster1, cluster2]:
                    labels[j] = new_cluster
            
            # Update clusters dictionary
            clusters[new_cluster] = clusters.get(cluster1, [cluster1]) + clusters.get(cluster2, [cluster2])
            if cluster1 in clusters:
                del clusters[cluster1]
            if cluster2 in clusters:
                del clusters[cluster2]
        
        # Assign colors based on current labels
        unique_labels = np.unique(labels)
        color_mapping = {label: i for i, label in enumerate(unique_labels)}
        colors_current = [color_mapping[l] for l in labels]
        
        # Plot current clusters
        scatter = ax1.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=colors_current, cmap='rainbow', alpha=0.6)
        ax1.set_xlabel('Mean Daily Return (Standardized)')
        ax1.set_ylabel('Volatility (Standardized)')
        ax1.set_title(f'Hierarchical Clustering (Merge {frame}/{n_merges})')
        
        # Plot dendrogram up to current merge
        dendrogram(Z, ax=ax2, truncate_mode='lastp', p=min(20, len(clusters)), 
                   show_leaf_counts=True, color_threshold=Z[frame-1, 2] if frame > 0 else 0)
        ax2.set_title('Dendrogram')
        ax2.set_xlabel('Cluster Size')
        ax2.set_ylabel('Distance')
        
        return scatter,

    ani = FuncAnimation(fig, update, frames=n_frames, interval=800, blit=False)
    plt.close(fig)
    return HTML(ani.to_jshtml())

# --- DBSCAN Animation (Enhanced) ---
def animate_dbscan():
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    scatter = ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c='gray', alpha=0.6)
    ax.set_xlabel('Mean Daily Return (Standardized)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Volatility (Standardized)')
    ax.set_title('DBSCAN Clustering Animation')

    # More eps values to show gradual clustering
    eps_values = np.linspace(0.1, 0.8, 20)  # Wider range of eps values
    min_samples = 5

    def update(frame):
        ax.clear()
        if frame == 0:
            scatter = ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c='gray', alpha=0.6)
        else:
            eps = eps_values[frame-1]
            db = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=min_samples).fit(X)
            labels = db.labels_
            
            # Count clusters (excluding noise)
            n_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
            
            scatter = ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=labels, cmap='rainbow', alpha=0.6)
            ax.set_title(f'DBSCAN (eps={eps:.2f}, clusters={n_clusters})')
        
        ax.set_xlabel('Mean Daily Return (Standardized)')
        ax.set_ylabel('Volatility (Standardized)')
        return scatter,

    ani = FuncAnimation(fig, update, frames=len(eps_values)+1, interval=600, blit=False)
    plt.close(fig)
    return HTML(ani.to_jshtml())

# Display all three animations with titles
print("K-Means Clustering Animation:")
display(animate_kmeans())

print("\nHierarchical Clustering Animation:")
display(animate_hierarchical())

print("\nDBSCAN Clustering Animation:")
display(animate_dbscan())

# Generate final static comparison plot
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))

# K-Means final
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42).fit(X)
axes[0].scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=kmeans.labels_, cmap='rainbow', alpha=0.6)
axes[0].scatter(kmeans.cluster_centers_[:, 0], kmeans.cluster_centers_[:, 1], 
                c='red', marker='x', s=200, linewidths=3)
axes[0].set_title('K-Means (k=4)')

# Hierarchical final
Z = linkage(X, method='ward')
hierarchical_labels = fcluster(Z, 4, criterion='maxclust')
axes[1].scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=hierarchical_labels, cmap='rainbow', alpha=0.6)
axes[1].set_title('Hierarchical (4 clusters)')

# DBSCAN final
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=0.5, min_samples=5).fit(X)
axes[2].scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=dbscan.labels_, cmap='rainbow', alpha=0.6)
axes[2].set_title(f'DBSCAN (eps=0.5, {len(set(dbscan.labels_))-1} clusters)')

for ax in axes:
    ax.set_xlabel('Mean Daily Return (Standardized)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Volatility (Standardized)')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
